CXi1eCpVyCEu-rQ7p1fTsA
PROS: * The location cannot be beat. The place sits between a gorgeous little park and the edge of the arts district. Everywhere you look there's incredible food and interesting events just a short walk away.  * The neighbors. Being in the Downtown Bubble means you'll run into the same people over and over again, as well as their pets. For the most part, everyone living at Roosevelt Square is fairly young, active, and friendly.  CONS: Everything else * The property is poorly maintained, despite first glances. The entry gates are constantly broken - either permanently locked with a malfunctioning fob detector, or permanently wide open. The parking garage gates are the same story. Several times I found myself either locked in or out, with no clue how to get through. I advise you to get to know your neighbors so you can call them in these situations and have them let you in. This will happen a lot. * Management is AWFUL. Every day you will receive a poorly spelled, poorly written update on some kind of emergency event (water shut off, gates not working, fire doors malfunctioning). * Maintenance is a toss up. The staff themselves are great and very knowledgeable and friendly. But it may take anywhere from a few hours to a few days for them to show up. I had a malfunctioning smoke alarm attached to a vaulted ceiling going off for 5 days before management sent someone. This was after sending multiple service requests and pleading with office staff to take it seriously. Maintenance staff will also show up unannounced, so beware of wearing headphones or taking showers during the day because more than once I was surprised when I found a stranger hunched over in my living room. * From 2014-2016 our water was shut off 45 times for "emergency repairs" (see image). In February of 2016 alone it was shut off 7 times. * Bike theft is rampant. If you have a bike, do not leave it locked up in the stairwells. * Although the parking garages have security cameras at the entrances, they are non-functioning. I discovered this after my husband's car was backed in to and we asked if we could review the footage. There was no footage. * There are two enormous dumpsters in Building C's garage labeled RECYCLE and CARDBOARD ONLY. Turns out they are neither and everything in them is picked up by the regular garbage collector. The only true recycle container is in Building A's garage. * The first floor hallways are prone to flooding (see image) and are rarely, if ever, cleaned. This place is very pet friendly, but many of the animals seem to have trouble holding it and are known to relieve themselves inside. Poop is only cleaned up if enough of the residents begin to make a fuss over it, and often times other residents give in and take care of it because they're just sick of seeing it every day. Urine is never washed away, so beware the discolored areas.

